*Kubernetes Ingress Controller Microservices Project Documentation*

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Project Overview:
 [This project demonstrates the deployment of two microservices (Home and Mobile) on AWS EKS, using
 Docker, Kubernetes, Helm, and NGINX Ingress Controller. The project follows a real DevOps workflow:
 containerization → deployment → service exposure → ingress routing.]

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 *Module 1 — Docker Image Creation*
 We created two frontend applications: home and mobile. - Directory structure: 
 <1> [  mkdir mobile
        cd mobile
        mobile.html
        Dockerfile  ]
 <2>  [  mkdir home
         cd home
         home.html
         Dockerfile  ]

(Dockerfiles were created for both microservices and images were pushed to Docker Hub.) 

- Commands used: 
[  docker build -t <dockerhub-user>/home-frontend:1.0 .
   docker push <dockerhub-user>/home-frontend:1.0
   docker build -t <dockerhub-user>/mobile-frontend:1.0 .
   docker push <dockerhub-user>/mobile-frontend:1.0  ]

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 *Module 2 — Kubernetes YAML Files*
 We wrote Kubernetes manifests for both microservices.

 Files created:
• home-deploy.yml
• home-service.yml
• mobile-deploy.yml
• mobile-service.yml
• ingress.yml
[ These define: - Deployments - ClusterIP Services - Ingress Rules for /home and /mobile]

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
*Module 3 - Creating AWS EKS Cluster*
Steps performed: 1. Installed AWS CLI and configured credentials (aws configure). 
2. Installed IAM Authenticator. 
3. Created EKS cluster with proper IAM policies. 
4. Ran: [  aws eks update-kubeconfig to connect CloudShell/EC2 with the EKS cluster.  ] 
5. Verified cluster: [  kubectl get nodes  ]

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

*Execution Steps*

 Step 1 — Apply Kubernetes Resources
 Applied all deployment and service YAML files: 

  [  kubectl apply -f home-deploy.yml
     kubectl apply -f home-service.yml
     kubectl apply -f mobile-deploy.yml
     kubectl apply -f mobile-service.yml  ]

Checked services using: 
  [  kubectl get svc  ]

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 2 — Install Helm & NGINX Ingress Controller. We installed Helm and used it to deploy the official Kubernetes Ingress-NGINX controller: 
   
   [ helm install nginx-ingress ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx   
    --namespace ingress-nginx   
    --create-namespace   
    --set controller.service.type=LoadBalancer ]
 (This created an AWS LoadBalancer for our ingress)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 3 — Cleanup & Reinstallation (If Needed)
We sometimes needed to uninstall: 
[  helm uninstall nginx-ingress -n ingress-nginx  ]
(Then reinstall using Helm again.)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 4 — Apply Ingress Resource
Applied ingress file: 
[  kubectl apply -f ingress.yml  ]
 Waited 60–90 seconds for the LoadBalancer DNS to update.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 5 — Test Microservices
We copied the LoadBalancer DNS: 
[  http://<ELB-DNS>/home
   http://<ELB-DNS>/mobile  ]
 Both applications loaded successfully → Project Completed.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


#_This is a complete, production-style Kubernetes microservices project_# :)
